commit.message:
WSDD: management of extended discovery time revisited (see also #e63b1ac)

See #e63b1ac for problem description and workaround method being used

The criterion of applying extended time was simplified. Instead of looking
for unpaired WSDD/MDNS device we simply compare count of WSDD/MDNS devices,
discovered so far, with problematic model names

This change not only makes things conceptually simpler, but also allows to
take in account MDNS-devices early, with not yet completed discovery/resolving
process
airscan-discover: fixed valgrind warning

MDNS: fix discovery if device misses IPv6 address or so (see #326)

This change adds ZEROCONF_PUBLISH_DELAY support for MDNS. The idea is
when at leas IP address is discovered, don't wait forever until all
related AvahiServiceResolver are finished or timed out, but limit
the wait time by ZEROCONF_PUBLISH_DELAY parameter (1000 milliseconds
for now).

Without this measure, if IPv6 address of device is not available at all,
we will know that only when AvahiServiceResolver times out, which is a
bit too late.

WSDD: WSDD_PUBLISH_DELAY renamed to ZEROCONF_PUBLISH_DELAY and made public

This constant makes sense (and planned to be used) for MDNS too, so it
is moved to the public header and renamed to be protocol-neutral.
MDNS: more accurate ipv4/ipv6 reporting in error messages

commit.message: added Brother and Epson scanners
Added HP M130fn; M130fw marked as supporting eSCL (closes #248)

WSDD: WS-Discovery reliability improved for Pantum devices

WS-Discovery implementation contains a trade-off between reliability
and response time.

To discover devices it sends Probe requests for some time in a hope
that all devices will be able to respond within this time limit. The
longer this time, the more reliable the search but the more time it
takes. And we cannot make this time dynamically adaptive, because we
don't have a priori knowledge about devices to be found.

The currently chosen discovery time, 2500 milliseconds (WSDD_DISCOVERY_TIME)
looks the reasonable trade-off in most cases. However, for many Pantum
devices it is often not enough for reliable discovery.

The implemented solution was to increase this time up to 5000 milliseconds,
if potentially problematic (Pantum for now) devices were discovered on a
network, using DNS-SD.

The list of problematic models may grow in a future, for now it contains
only Pantums, but implementation allows it to be easily extended.

airscan-discover: -fast option renamed to -test-fast; added -test-auto

These options are primarily purposed for testing, not for regular use

airscan-discover: added -fast option

Unlike sane-airscan, airscan-discover used to always work in a
"full" WS-Discovery mode (in the sane-airscan the mode is configurable
and default is "fast").

This option allows to airscan-discover in the "fast" mode.
Its primary purpose is to debug the "fast" discovery mode.
zeroconf_init_scan() function was declared, but never used/implemented
Cosmetic
When formatting IP address, append zone suffix only to link-local addresses

Fixed '%' escaping (zone suffix delimiter) in http_uri_set_host_addr

Literal IPv6 URLs, created from non-literal URLs, discovered by WSD,
didn't have correct escaping of the '%' zone delimiter
WSDD: names/indices of network interfaces made visible in logs

MDNS: fixed discovery of IPv6 addresses (fixes #320)

DNS-SD discovery of IPv6 addresses was not very reliable. IPv6 addresses
often were missed in discovery results.

The problem seems to be in Avahi. avahi_service_resolver_new() didn't
report IPv6 reliably when aprotocol == AVAHI_PROTO_UNSPEC.

So we have to start two separate resolvers: first for AVAHI_PROTO_INET
and second for AVAHI_PROTO_INET6
WSDD: small refactoring

WSDD: remove IP_MULTICAST_LOOP/IPV6_MULTICAST_LOOP socket options

IP_MULTICAST_LOOP/IPV6_MULTICAST_LOOP socket options removed from
the UDP sockets used for WS-Discovery

It allows discovery to work with WSD simulator running on a same
host and doesn't cause any regression.

The simulator is currently being developed for testing purposes.

Resolve non-literal host names discovered by WS-Discovery

Some devices (for now, all Pantum MFPs known to have this behaviour)
report their XAddrs/Endpoints URLs using device names, not literal
IP addresses.

It is not good for several reasons:
  * things become slower, because symbolic (non-literal) URL needs to
    be resolved every time it is being used
  * the name that device uses is not necessarily resolvable via DNS
    (depends on device configuration; often default name is used)
  * it adds extra dependency on local DNS which makes things more complex
    and less predictable
  * DNS-SD (eSCL) and WSD instances of the same device are not merged
    automatically, if UUID is not the same between protocols (as with Pantum)

With this change, non-literal device names in URLs are being resolved,
using Avahi MDNS resolver. I believe in most cases it is better that
using generic DNS, because:
  1. Nobody guarantees that device name is DNS-resolvable
  2. Avahi offers asynchronous API which plays well with overall
     sane-airscan asynchronous architecture

This change also brings some general refactoring of the zeroconf
code, required to implement these changes.

ESCL: workaround for HP Deskjet 3520 series over IPP over USB

This device returns Location: http://CN26F178X605SZ.03f011b0.hpLedmUSB/...
instead of expected http://localhost/... as response to the ScanJobs
request (please notice the hostname).

We actually used to ignore hostname in the ScanJobs response in
assumption that device may not have a strong knowledge of its own
hostname, but a while ago this logic was occasionally broken.
This patch restores that behavior.
